\begin_body

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
This section illustrates the role of reshoring policy in supporting innovation.
 Reshoring policy can be rationalized due to two spillovers.
 Either, offshoring substitutes for R&D which previously benefit other firms,
 or offshoring directly affects R&D productivity internally, or externally
 .....
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Theoretical Model
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Theoretic-Model"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider an environment with a two-tiered production network.
 Assembly firms, indexed by 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, sell differentiated varieties to consumers.
 Supplier firms, indexed by 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, sell inputs used in production by the assembly firms.
 Both types of firms may alter their productivity through innovation, represente
d by 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\boldsymbol{I}_{j},\boldsymbol{I}_{f}\}$
\end_inset

, or production structure, represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\boldsymbol{\omega}_{j},\boldsymbol{\omega}_{f}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Two state variables, summarizing aggregate R&D and production structure
 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\boldsymbol{\mathcal{I}},\boldsymbol{\Omega}\}$
\end_inset

, will depend on firm-level choices and affect the innovation process.
 Factor prices are determined by the production of an outside good, which
 serves as numeraire.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
I interpret the model results as characterizing optimal policy for one sector,
 sufficiently small that outcome on this sector do not affect economy-wide
 aggregates like factor prices or preferences.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Technology.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I specify technology in terms of a upstream and downstream firm's  cost
 of production:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{alignedat}{2}\text{c_{f,j}\left(\boldsymbol{I}_{f},\boldsymbol{\omega}_{f}\right)} & \text{ and } & c_{j}\left(\boldsymbol{p}_{j,I},\boldsymbol{I}_{j},\boldsymbol{\omega}_{j}\right)\end{alignedat}
.
\]

\end_inset

Each firm can affect productivity through innovation 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\boldsymbol{I}_{j},\boldsymbol{I}_{f}\}$
\end_inset

 - potentially along a number of input-specific, buyer-specific, or country-spec
ific dimensions.
 Each firm chooses a production structure that alters costs, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\boldsymbol{\omega}_{j},\boldsymbol{\omega}_{f}\}$
\end_inset

.
 In the empirical model, this will representation location decisions - both
 the choice of where to produce and where to do R&D - and firm-to-firm linkages
 made between suppliers and buyers.
 Downstream costs additionally depend on a vector of input prices, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}_{j,I}=\{\tilde{p}_{f,j}\}_{f}$
\end_inset

, provided by upstream firms.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The dependence of costs on factor prices is suppressed into the choice of
 production structure 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{j},\omega_{f}$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 may denote the location of production.
 If locations vary only in the cost of labor, differences in cost under
 various values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 simply reflects difference in wages.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Innovation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Innovation is expressed as the outcome of a an R&D process:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{I}_{f}=\boldsymbol{I}_{f}\left(\boldsymbol{\iota}_{f},\boldsymbol{\omega}_{f},\boldsymbol{\mathcal{I}},\boldsymbol{\Omega}\right)\text{ and }\boldsymbol{I}_{j}=\boldsymbol{I}_{j}\left(\boldsymbol{\iota}_{j},\boldsymbol{\omega}_{j},\boldsymbol{\mathcal{I}},\boldsymbol{\Omega}\right).
\]

\end_inset

Innovation is directly controlled by firms through R&D expenditure 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\boldsymbol{\iota}_{f},\boldsymbol{\iota}_{j}\}$
\end_inset

, which may be a vector-valued input due to country-specific or function-specifi
c R&D expenditures that contribute differently to innovation.
 The productivity of R&D expenditure varies with production structure.
 This reflects interactions between innovation and manufacturing activity
 within-firm that spur innovation including learning by doing, tacit knowledge
 transfers between workers, increased iteration speed, or joint problem-solving.
 Additionally, R&D productivity is affected by R&D spillovers, summarized
 by the state variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{I}}$
\end_inset

, and production structure spillovers captured by 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\Omega}$
\end_inset

.
 The former captures standard Marshallian forces in R&D, while the later
 captures across-firm spillovers from production structure to R&D including
 knowledge diffusion arising from suppliers and buyers coordination or labor
 mobility across facilities operated by many firms.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For example, there may be country-specific aggregate R&D levels that depend
 only on R&D spending done in those countries.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
and through an aggregate state 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The aggregates state - which includes moments of R&D expenditure, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{I}}$
\end_inset

, and industry structure, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\Omega}$
\end_inset

 - additionally affect costs.
 The state variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{I}}$
\end_inset

 represents a standard form of Marshallian externalities from collective
 knowledge production, while aggregate industry 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\Omega}$
\end_inset

 structure capture other forms of spillovers like geographic agglomeration
 forces.
 These aggregates can be multi-dimensional and depend differently on the
 components of R&D and production structure.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Policy.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A planner will have the opportunity to affect the all margins of firm adjustment.
 In particular, I write final prices 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{p}_{j}$
\end_inset

, input prices offered by suppliers 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\bar{p}_{f,j}$
\end_inset

 and faced by buyers 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{p}_{f,j}$
\end_inset

, and R&D costs 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\bar{r}_{j,k},\bar{r}_{f,l}\}$
\end_inset

 as a function of the underlying variables and policy wedges: 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{alignedat}{2}\text{Final Price:} & \quad & \bar{p}_{j}= & \left(1-t_{j}\right)p_{j},\\
\text{Input Prices:} & \quad & \bar{p}_{f,j}= & \left(1-t_{f}\right)\left(1-t_{f,j}\right)p_{f,j},\\
\text{Downstream R\&D Cost:} & \quad & \bar{r}_{j,k}= & \left(1-s_{j,k}\right)r,\\
\text{Upstream R\&D Cost:} & \quad & \bar{r}_{f,k}= & \left(1-s_{f,k}\right)r.
\end{alignedat}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{alignedat}{1}\bar{p}_{j}= & \left(1-t_{j}\right)p_{j},\\
\bar{p}_{f,j}= & \left(1-t_{j,j}\right)p_{j},\\
\tilde{p}_{f,j}= & \left(1-s_{f,j}\right)p_{f,j},\\
\bar{r}_{j,k}= & \left(1-s_{j,k}\right)r_{j,k},\\
\bar{r}_{f,l}= & \left(1-s_{f,l}\right)r_{f.l}.
\end{alignedat}
\]

\end_inset

The indices 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 are for each separate dimension of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\iota}_{j}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\iota}_{f}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{I}_{j}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{I}_{f}$
\end_inset

 may consist of location-specific R&D components that differentially affect
 cost according to xxx.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In addition, I assume that the cost of a particular production structure
 takes the following form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bar{f}\left(\boldsymbol{\omega}_{f}\right)=f\left(\boldsymbol{\omega}_{f}\right)+\phi\left(\boldsymbol{\omega}_{f}\right)\text{ and }\bar{f}\left(\boldsymbol{\omega}_{j}\right)=f\left(\boldsymbol{\omega}_{j}\right)+\phi\left(\boldsymbol{\omega}_{j}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\phi(\boldsymbol{\omega}_{f}),\phi(\boldsymbol{\omega}_{j})\}$
\end_inset

is a tax/subsidy associated with a production structure choice.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Profit Maximization.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Downstream firms determine final prices, R&D expenditures, and firm structure
 to maximize profits:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\pi_{j}=\max_{\bar{p}_{j},\boldsymbol{I}_{j},\omega_{j}}q_{j}\left(p_{j}\right)\left(\bar{p}_{j}-c_{j}\left(\boldsymbol{p}_{j,I},\boldsymbol{I}_{j},\boldsymbol{\omega}_{j}\right)\right)-\boldsymbol{\bar{r}}_{j}\boldsymbol{I}_{j}-\bar{f}\left(\boldsymbol{\omega}_{j}\right).\label{eq: Downstream Profits}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Downstream firms each face a residual demand curve arising from consumer
 demand and wield some monopoly power.
 I assume that R&D resources are in perfectly elastic supply at a cost 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\bar{r}}_{j}$
\end_inset

 to the firm.
 Finally, each production structure is associated with fixed cost payment.
 Upstream firms face a functionally equivalent 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Likewise, upstream firms face a similar profit maximization problem:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\pi_{f}=\max_{\left\{ \bar{p}_{f,j}\right\} _{j},\boldsymbol{I}_{f},\omega_{f}}\sum_{j}q_{f,j}\left(p_{f,j}\right)\left[\bar{p}_{f,j}-c_{f,j}\left(\boldsymbol{I}_{f},\boldsymbol{\omega}_{f}\right)\right]-\boldsymbol{\bar{r}}_{f}\boldsymbol{I}_{f}-\bar{f}\left(\boldsymbol{\omega}_{f}\right)\label{eq: Upstream Profits}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where demand arises from the assembly firms' input expenditure, and profits
 come from the sum of input sales to all assembly firms.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Aggregate State.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The firm-level choices of R&D expenditure and production structure determine
 the R&D state and industry structure.
 And these aggregate can be multi-dimensional functions of the firms' choices:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\mathcal{I}}=\boldsymbol{\mathcal{I}}\left(\{\boldsymbol{\iota}_{f},\boldsymbol{\iota}_{j}\}\right)\text{ and }\boldsymbol{\Omega}=\boldsymbol{\Omega}\left(\{\omega_{f},\omega_{j}\}\right).\label{eq: Aggregation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


