\begin_layout Plain Layout
This connects to Brander-Spencer (1985) but with a supply chain mechanism
 rather than Cournot competition: the channel is not output competition
 but R&D spillovers mediated through bilateral prices.
 The natural result is a proposition characterizing when beggar-thy-neighbor
 subsidies emerge (strong cross-country spillovers, so foreign subsidies
 reduce domestic R&D incentives) versus when free-riding dominates (weak
 spillovers, so each country prefers the other to subsidize).
 With the network structure, the answer will depend on the topology of which
 supplier-buyer links cross borders, connecting directly to your IHS data.
